p:
Besides CD4
 + T cells, macrophages are infected by HIV-1 in humans and by the simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV), the most closely related lentivirus to HIV, in non-human primates (NHP) (
 Cribbs et al., 2015; 
 Rodrigues et al., 2017). Recently, using a humanized mouse model, macrophages were shown to sustain HIV-1 infection and replication, even in the absence of T cells (
 Honeycutt et al., 2017; 
 Honeycutt et al., 2016). This is in line with several studies characterizing tissue macrophages, such as alveolar, microglia and gut macrophages, as reservoirs in HIV-1 patients undergoing antiretroviral therapy (
 Ganor et al., 2019; 
 Jambo et al., 2014; 
 Mathews et al., 2019; 
 Sattentau and Stevenson, 2016).
